label.text: Pollution and Dead Zones
Pollution from rivers containing high levels of fertilisers are causing coastal ‘dead zones’ in which the water contains low levels of oxygen.
Dead zones often form when fresh water with high levels of nutrients enters the ocean.
In warmer months, phytoplankton multiply rapidly because of the high level of nutrients and limit oxygen moving to deeper waters.

When the phytoplankton die, they fall to the seafloor and are broken down by bacteria. Any oxygen present is used up quickly by the decomposition of the phytoplankton, harming other marine animals and plants in the region that need oxygen to survive.
